deck: Mrs. Arakawa is the creator responsible for the award winning manga Stray Dog and for Hagane no Renkinjutsushi, also known as Fullmetal Alchemist. She often portrays herself as a cow.
description:
Hiromu Arakawa (荒川弘) is the creator of the Fullmetal Alchemist series in Japan. She's a private woman who prefers to illustrate herself as a cow wearing glasses in her manga series. This is partly becasue she is from a farming area of Japan that specialized in dairy.

One of Hiromu Arakawa's most defining characteristics is her habit of going to book stores and purchasing a variety of random books from used book stores. In the omake pages of Fullmetal Alchemist Vol. 21, Arakawa illustrated a short comic telling the story of how a book store cashier figured out her identity by just her last name and the assortment of books she had bought.
name: Hiromu Arakawa

deck: James Kochalka is a comic writer and artist, who is known for his whimsical, fun stories that often blend real with surreal environments, and his colorful artwork.
description:
James Kochalka was born in Springfeild, Vermont. His primary inspiration for writing comics comes from Daniel Clowes's Eightball. His comics have a child-like innocent tone (regardless of their often sexual content) and a simple style of drawing. He is prolific in his comic writing and his comics deal with a huge variety of subject matter. Some of his more popular works include American Elf, a comic diary which is continually updated, telling daily short stories from his own life, Monkey Verses Robot, a story with little text that deals with an epic battle between robots and monkeys, Super F*ckers (sic), dealing with an eponymous super-hero team that exploits their popularity and reputation to enjoy personal gain, and Conversation, a comic seres which he co-creates with one other writer per-issue, drawn around a conversation the two have.

Kochalka is also the front person and namesake of the rock n' roll band James Kochalka Superstar. The band's songs often correspond to his comics. JKS has recorded a theme song to Super F*ckers, and a song version of Monkey Verses Robot.  His song "Hockey Monkey" has been used in local advertising for hockey games in the Portland, Maine area.  Kochalka has been known to perform live for Comic Book Legal Defense Fund fundraisers and also to sometimes perform naked.
name: James Kochalka

deck: An associate editor for DC Comics who worked on Animal Man.
description:
Art Young was an editor during the early years of Vertigo. Active years of work for DC/Vertigo was during 1988 to 1995.  Art Young was set to be the editor of Disney's Touchmark comics.  Touchmark was a line that Disney announced before the "Disney Implosion" in 1991.  With Touchmark never coming getting a chance to be created, both Art Young and the attached properties where acquired by Karen Berger and DC comics to help launch the Vertigo Imprint. Titles acquired by Touchmark were:  Enigma, Sebastian O, Mercy, and Shadows Fall.
 
Art Young would help launch the Vertigo Imprint with editing series like Animal Man and Hellblazer along side minis such as Enigma.
 
Tank Girl and its Vertigo related titles were associated with Art Young.
name: Art Young

deck: Seth Fisher (July 22, 1972 - January 30, 2006) was an American comic book artist and penciller.
description:
Fisher possessed a unique and instantly recognizable drawing style. He first gained attention for his work on DC Comics' Green Lantern: Willworld, and was nominated for an Eisner Award for "Best Penciller/Inker" for Flash: Time Flies and Vertigo Pop! Tokyo.

In 2005, Fisher pencilled the five issue "Snow" storyarc of the Batman series Legends of the Dark Knight. (The story arc was written by Dan Curtis Johnson and J.H. Williams III.) Fisher provided the art for the Marvel mini-series Fantastic Four/Iron Man: Big in Japan (scripted by Zeb Wells) that appeared in 2005. (The series' final issue was published in early 2006.)

Fisher produced magazine and album covers in Finland and his adopted home of Japan. He also worked for a time for Presto Studios doing concept design work for the computer game Myst III: Exile.

Becker and Mayer publishers posthumously released a project titled Backpack Alarm, written by Shar Levine and Leslie Johnstone and featuring illustrations by Fisher. (The book provides a do-it-yourself guide to building a personal backpack security system.)

Fisher's death was made public by his friend and fellow artist J.H. Williams III on February 2, 2006, one day after the release of the final issue of the Fantastic Four/Iron Man mini-series. Fisher died instantly after falling seven stories from the roof of a hotel in Osaka. He is survived by his first wife April, second wife Hisako, and their son Toufuu.
name: Seth Fisher

deck: Daniel HDR is another of the new Brazilian artists working for Avatar Press, Marvel Comics and DC Comics.
description:
Daniel HDR (born 1974) is a Brazilian comic book artist.

Born in Porto Alegre (Brazil), in 1974, began as a professional in comics with only 14 years, at first participating in illustrations for comic books that offered space for the reader’s art, and soon working as an illustrator for local publishers as Press Editora, D’Arte, Ondas, and others.

In 1995, start publishing at the north-american comics publishers and Dark Horse Press. For the latter, developed the official adaptation for manga of the animated series Digimon.

In 2005, sign as exclusive artist with Avatar Press . Start a long work at Lady Death books (Classic Lady Death and Medieval Lady Death), with Lady Death's creator Brian Pulido. In 2006 your work with Pulido in Mini-Series (published on Avatar Press) are nominated as BEST SCREEN-TO-COMIC ADAPTATION, on the TV .

His new works including X-Men Forever (#22), Marvel/Rittenhouse sketchcards series (Spider man Arquives, X-Men Arquives, Marvel - 70th Anniversary, Marvel Heroes and Villains series), concept art to electronic games (Marvel Ultimate Alliance 2) and DCUOnline - Prestige Format comics adaptation (DC Comics).
name: Daniel HDR

deck: S.C. Ringgenberg, comics writer, editor and historian.
description:
Ringgenberg has written comic book scripts for D.C.: Weird War, House of Mystery, Robin 3000 miniseries, etc. For Marvel, wrote for Moon Knight, Savage Sword of Conan, What if...? For Red Circle wrote scripts for The Black Hood, For Heavy Metal have written comics scripts, reviews, interviews and articles during the mid-80s and again since 1999 as the regular columnist for Dossier.

Many other articles and interviews for The Comics Journal, Gauntlet, The Betty Pages, and many others. Ringgenberg was one of the contributing writers on Al Williamson: HIdden Lands, and has contributed extensively to the notes for Russ Cochran's E.C. Library reprint set.
